Both additions are exactly right. Here's a summary of everything that was added to `common/chat.cpp`:

---

### What was added (two additions, no existing code touched)

**1. New handler function — lines 1519–1540**, inserted between the closing `}` of `common_chat_params_init_gigachat_v3` and `namespace workaround`:

```cpp
static common_chat_params common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(
        const common_chat_template &          tmpl,
        const autoparser::generation_params & inputs) {
    common_chat_params data;

    // Mistral Instruct v0.3 format: user turns are wrapped with [INST]/[/INST],
    // any system message is prepended to the first user turn inside [INST], and
    // assistant turns are terminated with </s>.  The template itself already
    // encodes that structure, so we just need to apply it and set up a plain
    // content parser -- this format has no special tool-call tokens.
    data.prompt            = common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl(tmpl, inputs);
    data.format            = COMMON_CHAT_FORMAT_PEG_NATIVE;
    data.supports_thinking = false;

    auto parser = build_chat_peg_parser([&](common_chat_peg_builder & p) {
        return p.literal(inputs.generation_prompt) + p.content(p.rest());
    });

    data.parser = parser.save();

    return data;
}
```

**2. Detection block — lines 1713–1720**, appended at the end of `common_chat_try_specialized_template`, just before `return std::nullopt`:

```cpp
// Mistral Instruct v0.3 - uses [INST]/[/INST] turn markers without a [SYSTEM_PROMPT] token.
// The absence of [SYSTEM_PROMPT] is what distinguishes this format from Ministral/Mistral Large 3.
if (src.find("[INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[/INST]") != std::string::npos &&
    src.find("[SYSTEM_PROMPT]") == std::string::npos) {
    LOG_DBG("Using specialized template: Mistral Instruct v0.3\n");
    return common_chat_params_init_mistral_instruct_v3(tmpl, params);
}
```

---

**Design decisions:**

- **Detection logic**: checks for both `[INST]` and `[/INST]` (both must be present in the Jinja source), plus the **absence** of `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`. Because the Ministral 3 check runs earlier in the chain *and* requires `[SYSTEM_PROMPT]`, this block can never fire for a Ministral 3 template — the absence check is belt-and-suspenders for any future reordering.

- **Placement at the end of the chain**: `[INST]`/`[/INST]` are fairly common markers; placing the check last means every more-specific handler (GPT-OSS, Functionary, Kimi, LFM2/2.5, GigaChat) already had a chance to claim the template first.

- **Handler simplicity**: Mistral Instruct v0.3 has no special tool-call tokens (`[TOOL_CALLS]`, `[ARGS]`, etc.) and no reasoning tags, so the PEG parser is a single `content(rest())` rule. The prompt itself is produced by `common_chat_template_direct_apply_impl`, which runs the Jinja template as-is (system prepend to first user turn, `</s>` terminators — all encoded in the template).

